      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The determination of what is \"fundamental\" is usually left to the judiciary, which weighs the scope of the government interest against the depth of the religious claim. A strict, universal rule, while seemingly objective, risks violating core constitutional rights by forcing individuals to compromise their deepest beliefs. A functioning democracy aims for a balance, not an absolute, where the law is the standard but exceptions can exist for profound moral or religious reasons.",
      "source": "target",
